\section{Apocrypha}

\textit{Wikipedia}, ``Old Testament``, accessed 2010.07.12

\begin{quote}
The contents of the Old Testament canon vary from church to church: the Orthodox
canons have 51 books, while the major Protestant communions have 39.
\end{quote}

\textit{Wikipedia}, ``Biblical Apocrypha``, accessed 2010.07.12

\begin{quote}
This usage originated in Luther's Bible of 1534, which was the first to print
the Apocrypha as a separate inter-Testamental section. Luther was making a
polemical point about the canonicity of these books. As an authority for this
division, he cited St. Jerome, who in the early 5th century distinguished the
Hebrew and Greek Old Testaments, stating that books not found in the Hebrew were
not received as canonical.
\end{quote}

\textit{Bible Dictionary}, ``Apocrypha``

\begin{quote}
Apocrypha. Secret or hidden. By this word is generally meant those sacred books
of the Jewish people which were not included in the Hebrew Bible (see Canon).
They are valuable as forming a link connecting the Old and New Testaments, and
are regarded in the Church as useful reading, although not all the books are of
equal value. They are the subject of a revelation recorded in D\&C 91, in which
it is stated that the contents are mostly correct, but with many interpolations
by man.
\end{quote}

\subsection{Books of the Apocrypha}

\textit{Bible Dictionary}, ``Apocrypha``

\begin{quote}
 Among these books the following are of special value:

\begin{itemize}
 \item The First Book of Esdras
\item The Second Book of Esdras
\item The Book of Tobit
\item The Book of Judith
\item The rest of the chapters of the Book of Esther
\item The Book of the Wisdom of Solomon
\item The Wisdom of Jesus the Son of Sirach, or Ecclesiasticus
\item The Book of Baruch
\item The Epistle of Jeremy
\item The Song of the Three Children
\item The History of Susanna
\item Bel and the Dragon
\item The Prayer of Manasses
\item The First Book of the Maccabees
\item The Second Book of the Maccabees
\end{itemize}
\end{quote}

\section{Apostasy}

\textit{Guide}, ``Apostasy''

\begin{quote}
``A turning away from the truth by individuals, the
Church, or entire nations.''
\end{quote}

\textit{Preach My Gospel}, p. 33, ``Heavenly Father Reveals His Gospel in Every
Dispensation``
(my numbering added):

\begin{quote}
``All people have the gift of agency, which includes the freedom to accept or
reject the gospel as taught by the prophets and apostles.  Those who obey are
blessed, but those who (1) ignore, (2) reject, or (3) distort the gospel do not
receive God's promised blessings.``
\end{quote}

\subsection{The Great Apostasy}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Amos 8:11-12: A ``famine$\ldots$of hearing the words of the Lord.``
\item 2 Thes. 2:1-3: The Great Apostasy is predicted
\item Isa. 24:5: People would change the gospel
\item 1 Cor. 1:10-13: Paul was asking for unity
\item Acts 20:28-30: Prophecy of apostasy
\end{itemize}

\textit{Preach My Gospel},, p. 36, ``The Great Apostasy``
\begin{quote}
``Investigators must understand that a universal apostasy occurred
following the death of Jesus Christ and His Apostles.``
\begin{itemize}
 \item ``The Church of Jesus Christ is built on a foundation of apostles and
prophets``
(Eph. 2:19-20; 4:11-14).
\item ``People rejected and killed Jesus Christ and the Apostles`` (Matt. 24:9,
1
Ne.
11:32-34, 2 Ne. 27:5).
\item ``$\ldots$many conflicts of doctrine arose.``
\item ``Throughout history, many people have sincerely believed in false creeds
and
doctrines.``
\item ``Therefore, a restoration, not a reformation, was required.``
\end{itemize}
\end{quote}

\subsection{Three Apostate Reactions}

(Based on a study from my Gospel Journal)


Three apostate reactions are:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Ignore
 \item Reject
 \item Distort
\end{itemize}
\textit{Preach My Gospel}, p. 33 (as quoted above)

\subsubsection{How do people today do these things?}

\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Ignore}: Be slackers. ``If I don't know the truth, I can't be
punished for not following it.'' ``One God, many religions.''
 \item \textbf{Reject}: Argue the gospel with members of the church; ``Bible
bash;'' speak badly
about the church, picket it, etc.
\item \textbf{Distort}: Believe in and or distort false doctrines (this kind of
apostasy occurs
from within).
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{How did this sort of thing occur in Christ's time?}
Hard to say since the gospel spread so quickly (perhaps a study could be made on
this?)
Persecution of the church.
False doctrine was taught.

\subsubsection{How do we personally ``stop the apostasy?''}
Search the scriptures, both the standard works and the words of the living
prophets; listen to church leaders, both general and local authorities.
Be obedient to our leaders and to God's commandments.
Base our personal beliefs directly on the scriptures and on the words of the
prophets, not on any contradicting personal opinions we may have.

