\section{Atonement}

Ezra Taft Benson, ``The Book of Mormon and the Doctrine and Covenants,''
\textit{Ensign}, May 1987, 83

\begin{quote}
``Just as a man does not really desire food until he is hungry, so he does not
desire the salvation of Christ until he knows why he needs Christ.
No one adequately and properly knows why he needs Christ until he understands
and accepts the doctrine of the Fall and its effect upon all mankind. And no
other book in the world explains this vital doctrine nearly as well as the Book
of Mormon.''
\end{quote}

\noindent Joseph Smith, \textit{Teachings of the Prophet Joseph Smith}, selected
by Joseph Fielding Smith, (1979), p.121

\begin{quote}
``The fundamental principles of our religion are the testimony of the Apostles
and Prophets, concerning Jesus Christ, that He died, was buried, and rose again
the third day, and ascended into heaven; and all other things which pertain to
our religion are only appendages to it.''
\end{quote}

	Note: I have often heard this referred to as saying the Atonement is the
main principle of our religion and that all other principles are only appendages
to it.  For example, see Jeffrey R. Holland, ``Missionary Work and the
Atonement,'' \textit{Liahona}, Oct 2001, 26.  I concur that what the Prophet
meant here was the atonement.

\

\noindent Tad R. Callister, \textit{The Infinite Atonement}, p. 128
\begin{quote}
	If suffering is proportionate to one's physical, intellectual,
spiritual, and emotional sensitivities, then the Savior suffered more than
mortal man, because he knew more, felt more, and cared more than any other
mortal had ever done.
\end{quote}

\noindent Alma 7:11-13:
``He suffered all of our infirmities so that he would know how to succor us.''

\

\noindent Gospel writers suggest that the suffering continued on the cross.  In
\textit{The Mortal Messiah}, Elder McConkie says, ``Could it be that this was
the period of His greatest trial, or that during it the agonies of Gethsemane
recurred and even intensified?''

\subsection{Atonement in the {\it Book of Mormon}}

After going through the index, I found the word ``atonement'' or
used in reference to the atonement of Jesus Christ in 17
chapters of the {\it Book of Mormon}, ``atone'' used in 4 others,
and ``atoning'' used in 1 other.  This count excludes of course
places where the concept of atonement is discussed but the
vocabulary word atonement is not.  The {\it Book of Mormon} has 22 +
33 + 7 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 29 + 63 + 16 + 30 + 1 + 9 + 15 + 10 = 239
chapters, so we get a form of atonement in 22/239 = 9.2\%  of all
chapters.  The {\it Book of Mormon} has the concept of the atonement
in it.

By contrast, the October 2013 General Conference had a form of the
word atonement with reference to the Atonement of Jesus Christ in
16/35 = 45.7\% of talks.  I wouldn't expect this number to match the
{\it Book of Mormon} total.

\section{Baby Blessings}

``Priesthood Ordinances and Blessings,`` \textit{Family Guidebook}, (2006)

\begin{quote}
``Every member of the church of Christ having children is to bring them unto the
elders before the church, who are to lay their hands upon them in the name of
Jesus Christ, and bless them in his name'' (D\&C 20:70). In conformity with this
revelation, only worthy men who hold the Melchizedek Priesthood may participate
in naming and blessing children. The ordinance of naming and blessing children
requires authorization from the presiding authority.

When blessing a baby, men who hold the Melchizedek Priesthood gather in a circle
and hold the baby in their hands. When blessing an older child, brethren place
their hands lightly on the child's head. The person who gives the blessing:
\begin{enumerate}
 \item Addresses Heavenly Father.
\item States that the blessing is given by the authority of the Melchizedek
Priesthood.
\item Gives the child a name.
\item Gives a priesthood blessing as the Spirit directs.
\item Closes in the name of Jesus Christ.
\end{enumerate}
\end{quote}


\textit{Encyclopedia of Mormonism}

\begin{quote}
BLESSING OF CHILDREN. When babies are just a few weeks old, they are usually
given a priesthood blessing for the special purpose of conferring a name by
which the baby will be known and bestowing promises based on spiritual
impressions regarding the baby's future life. A quality of prophecy attends this
process. If a baby's father is a worthy holder of the Melchizedek Priesthood, he
will usually pronounce the blessing, but it may be given by a grandfather, a
family friend, or any other qualified priesthood holder chosen by the baby's
parents. Babies are usually blessed in the presence of the congregation at a
fast and testimony meeting. However, the blessing may be given at other times
and places, such as in a hospital or home, if there is a special need.
\end{quote}

\section{Baptism}

``Covenant'', \textit{BD}

\begin{quote}
``Sometimes denotes an agreement between persons (1 Sam. 23: 18) or nations (1
Sam. 11: 1); more often between God and man; but in this latter case it is
important to notice that the two parties to the agreement do not stand in the
relation of independent and equal contractors. God in his good pleasure fixes
the terms, which man accepts. The same word is sometimes rendered ``testament.''
	``The gospel is so arranged that principles and ordinances are received
by covenant placing the recipient under strong obligation and responsibility to
honor the commitment. Thus the severe consequences to Ananias and Sapphira, who
deliberately broke their covenant and lied unto God (Acts 5: 1-11).''
\end{quote}

\subsection{The Baptismal Covenant}

We promise:
\begin{itemize}
 \item To be ``willing to take upon [oneself] the name of the Son''
 \item ``always remember him''
 \item ``keep his commandments'' (Moro. 4:3)
\end{itemize}

God promises:

\begin{itemize}
 \item Constant companionship of the Holy Ghost
 \item Remission of sins (Acts 2:38)
 \item Being born again (John 3:5)
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Baptism Performed Only After the Age of Accountability}

\begin{itemize}
 \item D\&C 68:27: Children are baptized when they are eight
 \item Moro. 8: The false doctrine of infant baptism is condemned
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Baptism Needs to Be Performed by Proper Authority}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Mosiah 21:53: ``[they] were desirous to be baptized; but there was none
in the land that had authority from God.``
\item Acts 19:1-6: Paul re-baptizes some people when he finds out they didn't
receive the Gift of the Holy Ghost by the laying on of hands
\item D\&C 22:1-4: ``enter ye in at the gate, as I have commanded, and seek not
to counsel your God``
\item Pres. Ezra Taft Benson, PMG p. 109:
 ``$\ldots$ The only problem the objector has to resolve for himself is whether
\textit{The Book of Mormon} is true. For if \textit{The Book of Mormon} is true,
then Jesus is the Christ, Joseph Smith was his prophet, The Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints is true, and it is being led today by a prophet
receiving revelation.''
\item Christ was baptized by proper authority; He showed us the example in being
baptized (2 Ne. 31:7) and taught baptism after His resurrection (3 Ne. 11:17-28)
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{How authority is received}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Heb. 5:4: ``called of God, as was Aaron''
 \item Exo. 4:14-16: Aaron was called through the prophet, Moses
 \item Num. 12:6, 8: ``If there be a prophet among you, I the Lord will make
myself known unto him in a vision''
\end{itemize}

