\section{The \textit{Book of Mormon}}

Gordon B. Hinckley, ``A Testimony Vibrant and True,'' \textit{Ensign}, Aug 2005,
2-6

\

\textit{On the challenge to read The Book of Mormon by the end of 2005:}
\begin{quote}
	``Without reservation I promise you that if each of you will observe
this simple program, regardless of how many times you previously may have read
the Book of Mormon, there will come into your lives and into your homes an added
measure of the Spirit of the Lord, a strengthened resolution to walk in
obedience to His commandments, and a stronger testimony of the living reality of
the Son of God.''
\end{quote}

Marion G. Romney, ``The Book of Mormon,'' \textit{Ensign}, Aug 2005, 8-11

\begin{quote}
``I feel certain that if, in our homes, parents will read from the Book of
Mormon prayerfully and regularly, both by themselves and with their children,
the spirit of that great book will come to permeate our homes and all who dwell
therein. The spirit of reverence will increase; mutual respect and consideration
for each other will grow. The spirit of contention will depart. Parents will
counsel their children in greater love and wisdom. Children will be more
responsive and submissive to the counsel of their parents. Righteousness will
increase. Faith, hope, and charity---the pure love of Christ---will abound in
our
homes and lives, bringing in their wake peace, joy, and happiness.``
\end{quote}

\subsection{The \textit{Book of Mormon} Answers the ``Questions of the Soul''}

Ezra Taft Benson, ``Flooding the Earth with The Book of Mormon'',
\textit{Ensign}, Oct. 2005, p. 61; also Oct. 1988 Conference

\begin{quote}
``Missionaries need to know how to use the Book of Mormon to arouse mankind's
interest in studying it, and they need to show how it answers the great
questions of the soul. Missionaries need to read with those they teach various
passages from the Book of Mormon on gospel subjects.''
\end{quote}

\noindent \textit{Questions I received on my mission}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Why can't I get a girlfriend? 2 Ne. 2: there is opposition in all things
 \item Why aren't we all equal? 2 Ne. 2: there is opposition in all things
 \item When is the Second Coming? What will happen then? 1 Ne. 22
 \item Christ was born of a woman? Alma 7 (v. 9-10): yes
 \item What does Christ expect of me?
 \item Why is the world so agitated? 2 Ne. 2: there is opposition in all things
 \item Why am I here in the U.S.A.? 1 Ne. 13: this is a blessed land
 \item Is it wrong to drink beer? Mosiah 22: story where drinking had bad
consequences; 2 Ne. 2:27: we are free to choose right from wrong
 \item What is God? Alma 22: v.10: the Creator; v. 12: He gave us His image; v.
18: we must abandon our sins to know him
 \item Is adultery forgivable? Alma 39: yes, if you repent
 \item Why do some people have more than others? 2 Ne. 2: there is opposition in
all things
 \item How should baptism be performed? 3 Ne. 11: v. 23: repentance; v.
25: authority, v. 26: by immersion
 \item If a person is living in sin with another, and dies, will that person be
saved? Alma 42: v. 3: we know right from wrong; v. 13: repentance, v.
16: opposition; v. 22: God would cease to be God without opposition; v. 24: the
truly penitent will be saved
 \item Will there be sadness in Heaven? 3 Ne. 28: v. 7: the Three Nephites would
be more blessed; v. 9: their sadness would be only because of the wickedness of
the world; v. 10: their joy will be complete
 \item How can I use my talents to serve the Lord? Moro. 6: v. 4: after baptism,
they were in the church; v. 5: what the church did
 \item Will I die soon? Alma 12: v. 27: it was declared that all men must die
 \item Where did God come from?
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The \textit{Book of Mormon} answers questions in two ways}

\textit{from my missionary study journal}

\begin{enumerate}
 \item It answers the great questions of the soul
\begin{itemize}
 \item Morm. 8:35: Mormon saw us: ``I speak unto you as if ye were present``
 \item 2 Ne. 9:50-51: ``feast upon that which perisheth not''
\end{itemize}
 \item It responds to objections or doubts
\begin{itemize}
 \item If The Book of Mormon is true, then the church is true and we have a true
and living prophet at its head.
Knowing this, we know that we must listen to and follow the prophet
The \textit{Book of Mormon} is tangible evidence of this.
\item Ezra Taft Benson, as quoted in \textit{Preach My Gospel}, p. 108-109
\begin{quote}
 $\ldots$ All objections, whether they be on abortion, plural marriage,
seventh-day worship, etc., basically hinge on whether Joseph Smith and his
successors were and are prophets of God receiving divine revelation $\ldots$

$\ldots$ The only problem the objector has to resolve for himself is whether
the \textit{Book of Mormon} is true.  For if the \textit{Book of Mormon} is
true, then Jesus is the Christ, Joseph Smith was his prophet, The Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints is true, and it is being led today by a
prophet receiving revelation.

Our main task is to declare the gospel and do it effectively.  We are not
obligated to answer every objection.  Every man eventually is backed up to the
wall of faith, and there he must make his stand. (\textit{A Witness and a
Warning}, p. 4-5)
\end{quote}
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{The \textit{Book of Mormon} and Families}

Henry B. Eyring, ``A Discussion on Scripture Study,'' \textit{Ensign}, Jul 2005,
22-26

\begin{quote}
Through the Book of Mormon the Lord can also teach us about being with and
serving people. This book reveals the will of the Lord for family life in a way
that the other scriptures don't even approach. I believe that is largely because
of its interesting structure. It's about families; it's about people's
relationships. It starts with families, it ends with families, and we come to
love these families.
\end{quote}

\subsection{The \textit{Book of Mormon} in the \textit{Bible}}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Ps. 85:11: ``Truth shall spring out of the earth''
 \item Isa. 29: 4, 11, 18: A ``sealed'' book (JS-H: 1:64-65)
 \item Ezek. 37:19: The ``stick'' of Joseph/Ephraim and the ``stick'' of Judah
(Gen. 49:22-26, Deut. 33:13-16)
 \item John. 10:16: ``other sheep''
 \item Rev. 14:6: ``an angel$\ldots$having the everlasting gospel to preach''
 \item Why? There was an apostasy (Amos. 8:11-12)
 \item John 21:25: ``there are also many other things which Jesus did ``
 \item 2 Pet. 1:20-21: ``no prophecy of the scripture is of any private
interpretation''
  \begin{itemize}
   \item The Book of Mormon is not a ``private interpretation'' of the
scriptures but is a
book of writings of ``holy men of God spake as they were moved by the Holy
Ghost.``
  \end{itemize}
 \item Heb. 13:8: Jesus Christ the same yesterday, and to day, and for ever.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{A Bible! A Bible!}

2 Ne. 29

\begin{itemize}
 \item v. 4: The Bible is a record of the Jews (only)
 \item v. 7-8: God communicates and has communicated with other peoples
 \item v. 9: God is the same today as he was yesterday
\end{itemize}

\vspace{1 em}

\noindent\textit{Preach My Gospel}, p. 187: ``Help People Resolve Their
Concerns''

\begin{quote}
``Sometimes people's concerns are like an iceberg. Only a small portion is
visible above the surface.''
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Why do people believe only in The Bible?}

\textit{from my missionary study journal}

\begin{quote}
The Bible is actually true.  This is in contrast to many churches and pastors
who are not true.
The Bible is something many people, including parents, have in common. There
isn't really anything else comparable.
It is taught that only The Bible is true.  There are passages in The Bible which
can be (mis)interpreted to corroborate this.
It's tradition, and traditions are hard to break.
\end{quote}

\subsection{Ezra Taft Benson on the \textit{Book of Mormon}}

\textit{From a Mission Training}

Ezra Taft Benson, ``The Book of Mormon and the Doctrine and Covenants'',
\textit{Ensign}, Jan. 2005, p. 10; also Apr. 1987 Conference

\begin{quote}
``It is important that in our teaching we make use of the language of holy writ.
Alma said, ``I … do command you in the language of him who hath commanded me''
(Alma 5:61).
	``The words and the way they are used in the Book of Mormon by the Lord
should become our source of understanding and should be used by us in teaching
gospel principles.''
\end{quote}

Ezra Taft Benson, ``Flooding the Earth with The Book of Mormon'',
\textit{Ensign}, Oct. 2005, p. 61; also Oct. 1988 Conference

\begin{quote}
``Missionaries need to know how to use the Book of Mormon to arouse mankind's
interest in studying it, and they need to show how it answers the great
questions of the soul. Missionaries need to read with those they teach various
passages from the Book of Mormon on gospel subjects.''
\end{quote}

Bruce R. McConkie, \textit{The Millenial Messiah}, p. 159, 170, 179

\textit{Not included in my original training, but also a good quote}

\begin{quote}
``Few men on earth either in or out of the Church, have caught the vision
of what the Book of Mormon is all about. Few are they among men who know the
part it has played and will yet play in preparing the way for the coming of Him
of whom it is a new witness. … The Book of Mormon shall so affect men that the
whole earth and all its peoples will have been influenced and governed by it. …
There is no greater issue ever to confront mankind in modern times than this: Is
the Book of Mormon the mind and will and voice of God to all men?''
\end{quote}

Ezra Taft Benson, ``The Book of Mormon---Keystone of Our Religion'',
\textit{Ensign}, Nov. 1986, p. 4

\begin{quote}
 ``In 1832, as some early missionaries returned from their fields of labor, the
Lord reproved them for treating the Book of Mormon lightly. As a result of that
attitude, he said, their minds had been darkened. Not only had treating this
sacred book lightly brought a loss of light to themselves, it had also brought
the whole Church under condemnation, even all the children of Zion. And then the
Lord said, ``And they shall remain under this condemnation until they repent and
remember the new covenant, even the Book of Mormon'' (D\&C 84:54-57) $\ldots$

	``If the early Saints were rebuked for treating the Book of Mormon
lightly, are we under any less condemnation if we do the same?''
\end{quote}

I then included teaching about how to better use The Book of Mormon in our
missionary work.

\subsection{Question: Why the Book of Mormon Given that We Have Latter-Day
Prophets?}

The Book of Mormon is the only book we push as missionaries.  It is the main
book of scripture that we read.

We have Latter-Day prophets.  The Doctrine and Covenants is great and has
doctrine above and beyond what the Book of Mormon has.  Prophets could add
anything.  Why rely on the Book of Mormon more?

Here are my thoughts.

\begin{enumerate}
 \item The people of the Book of Mormon actually existed.  The Book of Mormon
stands
as a witness that God speaks to all peoples.
\item The Book of Mormon has the doctrine that will bring us closer to Christ
than
anything else.  Anything more modern couldn't possibly be better.
\item  The Book of Mormon exists, so why not use it?  Why replace it?
\item  How could we have something like the Book of Mormon without all the
history
behind it?  It wouldn't be the same if it were a collection of abstract
revelations.  The stories and the doctrines we learn from the stories in the
Book of Mormon are in a sense "better" for our edification than dry instruction.
\item  We still have the other stuff to supplement our understanding of
doctrine.
\item The Book of Mormon is a record of a fallen people.  We can learn a lot
from
their fall.  (Pride was their fall.)  Our dispensation, however, will not fall.
\end{enumerate}

