 \item First theory: 1 day = 24 hours
 \item Second theory: 1 day = 1,000 years
 \item Third theory: 1 day = an undertermined length of time, an era
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Evolution}

I don't know much about scientific evidence of evoultion.
I do know that the scriptures are true.

\begin{itemize}
 \item Gen. 1:26-27
 \item Rom. 8:16-17
 \item Jer. 1:5
 \item \textit{Doctrines of Salvation} 1:139: ``if spontaneous generation could
be possible then,
is it possible now? If not, why not?''
 \item \textit{D of S} 1:139-40: ``when the time came for this earth to be
peopled, the Lord, our
God, transplanted upon it from some other earth, the life which is found here.''
 \item 2 Tim. 3:7
 \item 2 Thess. 2:11-12
 \item Pres. Gordon B. Hinckley, ``God Hath Not Given Us the Spirit of Fear'',
\textit{Ensign}, Oct. 1984, p. 5
\begin{quote}
 ``I remember when I was a college student there were great
discussions on the question of organic evolution. I took classes in geology and
biology and heard the whole story of Darwinism as it was then taught. I wondered
about it. I thought much about it. But I did not let it throw me, for I read
what the scriptures said about our origins and our relationship to God. Since
then I have become acquainted with what to me is a far more important and
wonderful kind of evolution. It is the evolution of men and women as the sons
and daughters of God, and of our marvelous potential for growth as children of
our Creator.''
\end{quote}
\end{itemize}


\section{Debt}

\begin{quote}
``Debt'', Gospel Topics (on LDS.org)

Since the early days of the Church, the Lord's prophets have repeatedly warned
against the bondage of debt. One of the great dangers of debt is the interest
that accompanies it. When it is necessary to incur debt, such as a reasonable
amount to purchase a modest home or to complete one's education, the debt
should be repaid as quickly as possible.
\end{quote}

\begin{quote}

``Debt'', {\it True to the Faith}, p. 48-49 (my italics added)

 If you do incur debt, such as a reasonable amount in order to purchase a
modest home or complete your education, {\it work to repay it as quickly as
possible and free yourself from bondage}. When you have paid your debts and
accumulated some savings, you will be prepared for financial storms that may
come your way. You will have shelter for your family and peace in your heart
\end{quote}


\begin{quote}
N. Eldon Tanner, ``Constancy and Change,'' {\it Ensign},
June 1982, 4

 ``I am convinced that it is not the amount of money an individual earns that
brings peace of mind as much as it is having control of his money. Money can be
an obedient servant, but a harsh taskmaster''
\end{quote}


\begin{quote}
Janene Wolsey Baadsgaard, ``Avoiding the Debt Trap,'' {\it Ensign}, Aug. 1996
(My italics added)

 With the wisdom of long experience, many older couples---both those who have
wisely avoided the debt trap and those who have learned from their
mistakes---often counsel young couples not to let money matter more than other
things in life. They don't regret money they didn't earn, degrees they didn't
get, or {\it honors they didn't obtain}. They do regret time they didn't spend
with each other, their children, their parents, and their friends. They realize
that commitment to the gospel of Jesus Christ and to truly loving family
relationships yields life's greatest satisfaction.
\end{quote}


\subsection{Scripture References}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Luke 16:10-11
 \item D\&C 19:35
 \item 2 Kgs. 4:7
 \item Prov. 22:7
 \item Rom. 13:8
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textit{True to the Faith}, ``Debt''

This book takes the stance that we ought to avoid debt because without it we
have much more security.

\begin{quote}
 ``If you do incur debt, such as a reasonable amount in order to
purchase a modest home or complete your education, work to repay it as quickly
as possible and free yourself from bondage.''
\end{quote}

Common sense says this is a risk-averse stance.  It makes sense from the
standpoint that we aren't maximizing our expected wealth we are maximizing our
probability of having enough.  Another point is that, as mentioned in the Black
Swan, the markets are thick-tailed.  A market crash can happen more than we
realize.  Wise advise in 2008 would have been to get out of debt before the
market crashed.  As members of the church, we ought not to discount prophetic
insight.

\subsection{Wants vs. Needs}

Joseph B. Wirthlin, "Earthly Debts, Heavenly Debts," \textit{Ensign}, May 2004,
42

\begin{quote}
``All too often a family's spending is governed more by their yearning than by
their earning. They somehow believe that their life will be better if they
surround themselves with an abundance of things. All too often all they are left
with is avoidable anxiety and distress.''
\end{quote}

N. Eldon Tanner, "Constancy Amid Change," \textit{Ensign}, Nov. 1979, 81
\begin{quote}
"Those who structure their standard of living to allow a little surplus, control
their circumstances. Those who spend a little more than they earn are controlled
by their circumstances. They are in bondage.''
\end{quote}

Gordon B. Hinckley, ``I Believe,'' \textit{Ensign}, Aug. 1992, 6

\begin{quote}
``Reasonable debt for the purchase of an affordable home and perhaps for a few
other necessary things is acceptable. But from where I sit, I see in a very
vivid way the terrible tragedies of many who have unwisely borrowed for things
they really do not need.''
\end{quote}

