\section{Faith}

\subsection{What Is Faith?}

\subsubsection{As Defined in Scripture}
\begin{itemize}
 \item Alma 32:21
Ether 12:6
Hebrews 11:1 (See JST)
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{As Defined in the Dictionary}

\textit{Wikipedia}, ``Faith'', accessed 2010.11.17

\begin{quote}
Faith is the confident belief or trust in the truth or trustworthiness of a
person, idea, or thing that is not based on proof.
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Greek Roots}

\textit{Wikipedia}, ``Faith in Christianity'', accessed 2010.11.17

\begin{quote}
The word "faith" $\ldots$ was primarily used
in the New Testament with the Greek perfect tense and translates as a noun-verb
hybrid; which is not adequately conveyed by the English noun. Pi'stis in the New
Testament context is a physical action, based upon a mental belief and sustained
with confidence. Belief, in this context is non-synonymous with faith because,
belief primarily conveys the mental action, thought of confidence, trust, and/or
firm persuasion, not the physical act. Depending on the context, the Greek word
may also be understood to mean "faithfulness" or "fidelity" (cf. 1 Thess 3:7;
Titus 2:10); indeed, Karl Barth consistently translates "pistis" as "the
faithfulness of God" in his commentary Epistle to the Romans.
\end{quote}

\subsection{Breaking Down the Concept of Faith}

\textit{True to the Faith}, "Faith" (with numbering added by me)

\begin{quote}
In order for your faith to lead you to salvation, it must be centered in the
Lord Jesus Christ (see Acts 4:10-12; Mosiah 3:17; Moroni 7:24-26; Articles of
Faith 1:4). You can exercise faith in Christ when you have an (1) assurance that
He exists, a (2) correct idea of His character, and a (3) knowledge that you are
striving to live according to His will.
\end{quote}

James 2:17-19

\begin{quote}
If we but believe in Christ, yet not keep His commandments--for we know that
through obedience to His commandments we receive both temporary blessings in
this life as well as, ultimately, the great eternal blessing of everlasting life
in His presence--then truly we do not have faith.
\end{quote}

Moroni 7:33

\begin{quote}
"And Christ hath said: If ye will have faith in me ye shall have power to do
whatsoever thing is expedient in me."
\end{quote}

\textit{Preach My Gospel},, p. 61

\begin{quote}
"Having faith in Christ includes$\ldots$"
Having "a firm belief that He is the Only Begotten Son of God and the Savior and
Redeemer of the World".
Recognizing "that we can return to live with our Heavenly Father only by relying
on His Son's grace and mercy."
Accepting and applying "His Atonement and His teachings."
Trusting "Him and what He says."
Knowing "that He has power to keep His promises."
\end{quote}

\textit{Thought from my missionary study journal}

\begin{quote}
Sometimes we receive blessings just by keeping a commandment; we are not
withheld the blessing because we don't exercise a great mental effort to believe
in Him; for example, we will have better health if we keep the Word of Wisdom.
	Great faith is important, however, for realizing great blessings and for
working miracles (the kind of miracles I would have liked to have "performed" on
my mission.)
\end{quote}

Joseph Smith, \textit{Teachings of the Presidents of the Church: Joseph Smith},
p. 160

\begin{quote}
``When the Lord commands, do it.''
\end{quote}

Pres. Thomas S. Monson, ``Great Expectations'', CES Fireside Jan 11, 2009

\begin{quote}
``Remember that doubt and faith cannot exist in the mind at the same time, for
one will dispel the other. Whereas doubt destroys, faith fulfills. An attitude
of faith brings one closer to God and to His purposes.''
\end{quote}

Stephen L. Richards, in \textit{Conference Report}, Oct. 1937, 39.

\begin{quote}
``Just say to those skeptical, disturbing, rebellious thoughts, ‘I propose to
stay with my faith, with the faith of my people. I know that happiness and
contentment are there and I forbid you, agnostic, doubting thoughts, to destroy
the house of my faith. I acknowledge that I do not understand the processes of
creation, but I accept the fact of it. I grant that I cannot explain the
miracles of the Bible, and I do not attempt to do so, but I accept God's word. I
wasn't with Joseph, but I believe him. My faith did not come to me through
science and I will not permit science to destroy it.'''
\end{quote}

