\section{The Fall}

``Agency and the Fall of Adam and Eve'', \textit{Preach My Gospel}, p. 49

\begin{quote}
``While Adam and Eve were in the garden, they were still in God's presence and
could have lived forever. They lived in innocence, and God provided for their
needs$\ldots$

	``$\ldots$they were cast out from the garden and out of God's physical
presence. This event is called the Fall. Separation from God's presence is
spiritual death. Adam and Eve became mortal---subject to physical death or
separation of the body and spirit$\ldots$''

	``They had moral agency or the ability to choose between good and evil.
This made it possible for them to learn and progress. It also made it possible
for them to make wrong choices and sin. In addition, they could now have
children, so the rest of God's spirit children could come to earth, obtain
physical bodies, and be tested. Only in this way could God's children progress
and become like Him.''
\end{quote}

\subsection{Was Adam's Transgression Really a Sin?}

Brigham Young, as quoted in \textit{Doctrines of Salvation} 1:104

\begin{quote}
``How did Adam and Eve sin? Did they come out in direct opposition to God and to
his government? No. But they transgressed a command of the Lord, and through
that transgression sin came into the world''
\end{quote}

Joseph Fielding Smith, ``The Fall of Adam Was Not a Sin'', \textit{Answers to
Gospel Questions}, 2:214

\begin{quote}
``The transgression of the law, contrary to the view of many, was not a sin. It
was not a sin any more than the transgression in the laboratory by a chemist in
combining two substances and creating another entirely different from the first.
It was not a sin to bring to pass mortality, a condition which was essential to
the eternal welfare of man.''
\end{quote}

\subsection{Difference between transgression and sin}

Note, 2011.07.03

\

\subsubsection{Transgress}

\noindent -verb (used without object)

\begin{enumerate}
 \item  to violate a law, command, moral code, etc.; offend; sin.
-verb (used with object)
 \item to pass over or go beyond (a limit, boundary, etc.): to transgress
bounds of
prudence.
 \item  to go beyond the limits imposed by (a law, command, etc.); violate;
infringe:
to transgress the will of god.
\end{enumerate}


\noindent Origin:
1520-30;  $<$ Latin transgressus  (past participle of transgredi  to step
across), equivalent to trans- trans-  + -gred-  (combining form of gradi  to
step; see grade) + -tus  past participle suffix, with dt  $>$ ss

\subsection{Sin}

\begin{enumerate}
 \item transgression of divine law: the sin of Adam.
 \item any act regarded as such a transgression, especially a willful or
deliberate
violation of some religious or moral principle.
 \item any reprehensible or regrettable action, behavior, lapse, etc.; great
fault
or offense: It's a sin to waste time.

-verb (used without object)
 \item to commit a sinful  act.
 \item to offend against a principle, standard, etc.

-verb (used with object)
 \item to commit or perform sinfully: He sinned his crimes without
compunction.
 \item to bring, drive, etc., by sinning: He sinned his soul to perdition.
\end{enumerate}


\noindent Origin:
before 900;  (noun) Middle English; Old English syn ( n ) offense, misdeed; akin
to German S\"unde, Old Norse synd  sin, Latin sons  guilty; (v.) derivative of
the
noun, replacing Middle English sin ( i ) gen, syn ( i ) gen, Old English
syngian,  itself derivative of the noun
%3

