I fear this supernal gift is being obscured by programs and activities and
schedules and so many meetings. There are so many places to go, so many things
to do in this noisy world. We can be too busy to pay attention to the promptings
of the Spirit.
\end{quote}

\section{Melchizedek}

Melchizedek or Malki Tzedek (from Hebrew malk-i s\'{e}deq) translated
as "my king (is) righteous(ness)")

\subsection{Who Was Melchizedek?}

From \textit{Mormon Doctrine}, ``Melchizedek''
\begin{quote}
Alma 13:19: Of all God's ancient high priests "none were greater."

His position in the priestly hierarchy of God's earthly kingdom was like unto
that of Abraham (Heb. 7:4-10), his contemporary whom he blessed (Gen. 14:18-20;
Heb. 7:1; Inspired Version, Gen. 14:17-40), and upon whom he conferred the
priesthood. (D. \& C. 84:14.)

Both bore the titles, Prince of Peace and King of Heaven - meaning King of Peace
(Alma 13:18; Inspired Version, Gen. 14:33, 36)

Alma tells us that "Melchizedek was a king over the land of Salem; and his
people had waxed strong in iniquity and abomination; yea, they had all gone
astray; they were full of all manner of wickedness; But Melchizedek having
exercised mighty faith, and received the office of the high priesthood according
to the holy order of God, did preach repentance unto his people. And behold,
they did repent; and Melchizedek did establish peace in the land in his days;
therefore he was called the prince of peace, for he was the king of Salem; and
he did reign under his father." (Alma 13:17-18.)

Paul, very obviously knowing much more about Melchizedek than he happened to
record in his epistles, gave as an illustration of great faith some unnamed
person who "wrought righteousness, obtained promises, stopped the mouths of
lions, Quenched the violence of fire." (Heb. 11:33-34.) From the Prophet's
inspired additions to the Old Testament we learn that Paul's reference was to
Melchizedek. "Now Melchizedek was a man of faith, who wrought righteousness; and
when a child he feared God, and stopped the mouths of lions, and quenched the
violence of fire." (Inspired Version, Gen. 14:26.)
\end{quote}

\subsection{Melchizedek and Shem}

D\&C 84:14: Abraham received the priesthood through Melchizedek, who received
it through the lineage of his fathers, even till Noah.

This implies (my interpretation) that Melchizedek was number one in the
patriarchal line at this time.

After Noah died, Shem would have been number one in the patriarchal line.

Jasher 16:11: ``And Adonizedek king of Jerusalem, the same was Shem, went out
with his men to meet Abram and his people, with bread and wine, and they
remained together in the valley of Melech.''

The Book of Jasher is apocryphal. From the online text where I copied this
verse:
\begin{quote}
	``This is one of the apochrypal Books of Jasher. There are several (as
many as five) separate works by this title, all composed much later than
Biblical times. This particular one is a translation of a Hebrew book printed in
1613. Sepir Ha Yasher, the Hebrew title of this book, means the 'Book of the
Upright', or 'the Upright or Correct Record'. This title was misread as
'Jasher', and at some point Jasher was treated as a proper name; however the
pronoun 'the' (hebrew 'ha') never preceeds proper names.

	``There is also another spurious Book of Jasher, published 1750,
	in which Jasher is treated as the name of the author.

	``This text covers much of the same ground as the traditional Mosaic
books of the Bible, from the creation of the world to the death of Moses, albeit
with several minor variations.''
\end{quote}

(According to \textit{Wikipedia}) John Taylor endorsed the theory that
Melchizedek was Shem

Bruce R. McConkie, \textit{Mormon Doctrine}: The line ``lineage of his fathers''
suggests to him that there ``at least two generations between Melchizedek and
Shem.''

Note, 2013.12.01: In Alma 13:18, we read that Melchizedek ``did
reign under his father''.

\section{Millennium}

\subsection{How is Satan bound in the Millennium?}

\textit{The Millennial Messiah}, p. 668:
Elder McConkie says that Satan will be bound by people choosing righteousness.
He makes the following points:
\begin{itemize}
 \item God did not bind Satan in the pre-mortal life because he lets Satan have
his agency.
 \item Later [p. 695-96] Elder McConkie talks about Satan being loosed
corresponding to
men ceding to apostasy and listening to him.  Elder McConkie notes that in 4th
Nephi the people were not influenced by Satan for a long time.
 \item In this way, the Book of Mormon mirrors the Millennium.  3rd Nephi is
like the
2nd coming and 4th Nephi is like the Millennium.  Mormon, then, is like the
final battle.
 \item Elder McConkie postulates that the post-millennium period in which Satan
is
bound will be 1,000 years.
\end{itemize}

question: how is this?  is the millennium + post-millennium like having a long
terrestrial period?

\subsection{Scripture Chain}

\begin{itemize}
 \item 1 Ne 22:15: No power because the wicked will be burned
 \item 1 Ne 22:26: No power because of the righteousness of the people
 \item Rev 20:1-3: [Symbolic] An angel will chain the dragon, cast him in a pit,
and he will be bound for a thousand years.  After that, he will be loosed for a
season.
 \item D\&C 88:110: When the angel sounds his trump for the 7th seal, Satan
will be bound
 \item D\&C 101:28: Satan shall not have power to tempt any man
 \item Just because we are righteous doesn't mean we can't be tempted.  For
example, Jesus was tempted (Heb. 4:15, Mosiah 3:7, TG: Jesus Christ, temptation
of)
 \item Idea: One possible interpretation is that Satan can't tempt man,
therefore he
has no power.  Satan has power today in more ways than just the power to tempt
us. (i.e. the church of the devil)
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Personal Lesson}

Lesson in humility: I am finding more sources which talk about Satan being bound
because people are righteous.  I had judged others who emphasized this point.
``Death'' during the Millennium

People in the Millennium will in fact pass on.  D\&C 101:29-31 talks about this.
It says that there will not be death like we know it, but when we are
``twinkled''
we will be caught up and received into our rest.
TPJS p. 268 says that immortal beings will frequently visit the earth.  This
wouldn't make sense if, like I had understood before, all resurrected people
just were here because no one would ``visit'' the earth.
In this sense, the Millennium will be a lot like life on earth today.

\subsection{Righteousness of the earth during the Millennium}

The wicked will be destroyed at the Second Coming and only Celestial and
Terrestrial level people will live on earth. (Gospel Principles, p. 263)
	People will still have agency. However, eventually everyone will confess
that Jesus Christ is the Savior. (Gospel Principles, p. 263)

\subsection{Christ will reign personally on the earth}

A of F 10 states this fact.  In TPJS p. 258, Joseph Smith said that ``Jesus will
reign over the saints and come down and instruct.''
	[Source?]  I read that Jesus will not dwell on the earth continually but
will make visits to the earth.  He will reign from heaven.

\subsection{Two World Capitals}

Jerusalem in the east and the New Jerusalem, or Zion (Independence, MO) in the
west.

Isa 2:3: ``for out of Zion shall go forth the law, and the word of the Lord out
of Jerusalem.''

Study 2010.11.12: the Hebrew roots indicate law refers to teaching or doctrine.
Contrary to what I had previously supposed, there appears to be no separation
between the two into a spiritual capital and a legal capital. (Am I sure?)

Ether 13: Jersualem for (scattered) Israel---recall that Jerusalem was promised
to Abraham and that the 10 tribes are to be restored---New Jerusalem for the
remnant of Joseph.
If I am interpreting this correctly, why would this be the design?
It is a symbol: Ether 13:6-9?
Joseph saved Israel and brought him to Egypt.
The Lord brought a remnant of Joseph out of Jerusalem and thereby saved them.

Old vs. New.
New = church today, Old = past traditions, etc.; the church is responsible for
the new city, the Jews for the old.
Zion will likely be built before the second coming.  Jerusalem exists even now.
First shall be last, last shall be first.

Fulfilling of covenants.
Joseph's is America.
Israel promised Canaan (restoration of the 10 tribes).

{\it Book of Mormon Reference Companion}:
Zion is also a holy city to be built on the American continent in the last days.

  This will be the New Jerusalem which will complement the original Jerusalem
existing in the eastern hemisphere. It will be a place of gathering for the
faithful as they prepare for Christ's second coming and will serve as a
governing center for his kingdom after his return (D\&C 45:64-71; 57:2-3; 2 Ne.
12:3; 3 Ne. 20:22; 21:23; Ether 13:1-12;   Moses 7:62).

Enoch to come down to meet New Jerusalem? (Moses 7:63)

Jerusalem the first city after the flood? (``New Jerusalem,'' Mormon Doctrine)

Is it possible that there are more major holy cities to be built up after the
Second Coming?

Conclusion for now: there will be two because that's just how it will be.  There
is a lot of symbolism with it though.

\subsection{Will Little Children Be Tested There?}

Bruce R. McConkie, ``Salvation of Little Children,'' Tambuli, Mar 1978, 3

\begin{quote}
Absolutely not! Any idea that they will be tested in paradise or during the
millennium or after the millennium is pure fantasy. Why would a resurrected
being, who has already come forth from the grave with a celestial body and whose
salvation is guaranteed, be tested? Would the Lord test someone who cannot fail
the test and whose exaltation is guaranteed? For that matter, all those billions
of people who will be born during the millennium, when Satan is bound, ``shall
grow up without sin unto salvation'' (D\&C 45:58) and therefore will not be
tested. ``Satan cannot tempt little children in this life, nor in the spirit
world, nor after their resurrection. Little children who die before reaching the
years of accountability will not be tempted.'' (Doctrines of Salvation,
2:56-57.)
Such is the emphatic language of President Joseph Fielding Smith.
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{When and with what stature will children be resurrected?}

Joseph F. Smith, \textit{Gospel Doctrine}, pp. 455-56
\begin{quote}
``Joseph Smith taught the doctrine that the infant child that was laid away in
death would come up in the resurrection as a child; and, pointing to the mother
of a lifeless child, he said to her: ‘You will have the joy, the pleasure, and
satisfaction of nurturing this child, after its resurrection, until it reaches
the full stature of its spirit.' There is restitution, there is growth, there is
development, after the resurrection from death. I love this truth. It speaks
volumes of happiness, of joy and gratitude to my soul. Thank the Lord he has
revealed these principles to us.''
\end{quote}

\noindent Joseph F. Smith, \textit{Gospel Doctrine}, p.453
\begin{quote}
It matters not whether these tabernacles mature in this world, or have to wait
and mature in the world to come, according to the word of the Prophet Joseph
Smith, the body will develop, either in time or in eternity, to the full stature
of the spirit, and when the mother is deprived of the pleasure and joy of
rearing her babe to manhood or to womanhood in this life, through the hand of
death, that privilege will be renewed to her hereafter, and she will enjoy it to
a fuller fruition than it would be possible for her to do here. When she does it
there, it will be with the certain knowledge that the results will be without
failure; whereas here, the results are unknown until after we have passed the
test.
\end{quote}

