\section{Planning}

\textit{Preach My Gospel}, p. 137

\begin{quote}
 You will be expected to devote all your time and attention to serving the
Lord, leaving behind all other personal affairs.
\end{quote}

{\it Note, 2013.04.20:} for the above quote, the mission is unique in that we
are devoted to one thing.  In real life, we are devoted to many things.  I
personally have found this hard because when one is giving all to a single
cause, one feels productive (and happy).  In my life, I have given up an
endeavor in which I would have given a lot of devotion (becoming an academic
mathematician) because of the other (more important) matters in which I am
involved.


\subsection{Goal Setting}

\textit{Preach My Gospel}, p. 146

\begin{quote}
Goals reflect the desires of our hearts and our vision of what we can
accomplish.
\end{quote}

{\it Thought:}
Effective goal setting and completing is difficult; it is something I have yet
to master.

\subsubsection*{Thought, 2013.04.20} Something which has helped me over
the past couple weeks is desire.  As I set goals these past two weeks, I have
done so with resolute commitment to keeping them. I decided that I really
wanted
to make and, more importantly, keep a few goals.

Goals reflect the desires of our hearts, as quoted above.  I had had a hard
time taking the desires of my heart and converting them to action.  I had
become implicitly convinced that it was OK to be lax with my goals and be lazy.
 I finally decided to invest in the desires of my heart and topple the desires
of the natural man.

\subsubsection{Note, Church, 2013.04.21}

During a lesson in Elders Quorum which touched on goal setting, a comment was
made about using motivational mechanisms to encourage one to complete goals.
For example, one could automatically have money deducted from one's account and
donated to some loathsome cause if he failed to keep his goal.
This contrasted with what I have been doing for the past couple weeks.
For me, if I set a goal, the act of setting a goal should be enough motivation
to keep it.  I am changing a lot of my choices away from the more comfortable
choice to the better choice.

For example, I know that it is good to wake early
and go to bed early. Because it is in the scriptures (D\&C 88:124) it is
actually very clear that waking and sleeping early is good.  On the other hand,
for a long time I had not been doing it, i.e.\ most of my post-mission life.
It is comfortable and stimulating to stay up late; it is very comfortable to
sleep late, especially if one had slept in late---I am a strong believer in at
least getting 8 or so hours of daily sleep.  So is the allure of sleeping late
and rising late more appealing than keeping the rule laid out in D\&C 88:124?
From a logical point of view, no of course not; in the long view of things I
feel better when I sleep and rise early.  Am I so weak that when faced with a
choice of an easy bad decision and a hard good decision, I am obligated to take
the easy?  I have decided, at least in this case and at least at this time,
that no, I am not so weak.

The final thought is that when crossing over from lazy to diligent, I had
originally planned to do it for a week only.  However, everything that I
planned to do for just a week was something that I thought was good for me, and
I really felt happy being diligent.  As a result, I extended my plan to do it
for just one week to a plan for doing it every week.

\subsubsection*{Notes from Church, 2009.01.04}

SMART goals = Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Realistic, with a Time Limit:
\begin{itemize}
\item Break it up
\item Write it down
\item Tell people
\item Change of heart
\item 10,000 reminders
\item Realistic
\item Prioritize
\item Pray/Involve God
\item Contingency plan
\item Reason why
\item ``Association brings assimilation'': you become who you hang out with
\end{itemize}

