\section{Pondering}

Thought 2011.06.09
\begin{quote}
Pondering on the scriptures is important and is often overlooked by me.  I often
think about scripture study as just keeping myself busy immersed in some kind of
scriptures.  Perhaps that ignores the point of scripture study--or studying in
general.

The general study point I miss by not pondering is that studying is not an end
but is a means to an end.  Study goals such as study for a half an hour or read
5 pages per day are useful but imperfect; they are useful because they are the
easiest to measure and carry out; they are imperfect because they have nothing
to do with the end goal.

In scripture study what is the end goal?  It can be that one needs to prepare
some kind of talk or lesson, but in my case, as someone who does not have to
give talks and lessons, what is the goal?  This is an interesting topic in and
of itself, and I don't have a complete answer.  My first thought is that the
goal of this life is to gain eternal life; therefore the goal of scripture study
should tie into me gaining eternal life.

The scripture specific element I miss by not pondering is revelation.  One does
not truly learn while studying the scriptures without receiving revelation.  And
how can one receive revelation without pondering; things of the spirit typically
do not come without our minds and hearts being opened.
\end{quote}

\begin{itemize}
 \item 1 Nephi 11:1:
Nephi was pondering when he received his vision; this, however, after he had
heard the words of the prophet (Lehi) and coupled with him (Nephi) having faith
in Christ.
\item D\&C 138:1-11 (esp. 1, 11):
Joesph F. Smith was pondering over a scripture passage when he was given the
vision which became section 138.
\item 2 Nephi 4:15:
Pondering linked to delight in the scriptures.
\item Hel. 10:2-3:
Nephi pondering and received a visit from an angel.
\item Moro. 10:3:
Part of "Moroni's Promise" is to ponder in one's heart.
\item D\&C 76:19:
It was while pondering that section 76 was given.
\item JS--H 1:12:
Joseph prepared himself to receive the First Vision by pondering.
\end{itemize}

