\vspace{1 em}

\noindent Clip from a Random Website:
http://www.patheos.com/Resources/Additional-Resources/Toward-Becoming-a-Gospel-S
cholar?offset=7\&max=1
\begin{quote}
Much, much more can and should be said about striving to become a gospel
scholar. Elder Bruce R. McConkie once went on to list other keys for unlocking
the gospel truths in the scriptures: learn of local customs and traditions,
distinguish between literal and figurative passages, and of course, ponder,
pray, and seek the spirit. All of this lays out a lifetime of rewarding
learning.

No one should expect to become a gospel scholar overnight. President Ezra Taft
Benson admonished faithful members of the Church to make the study of the
scriptures, especially the Book of Mormon, a lifetime pursuit. A gospel scholar
is always keenly aware of the distances yet to be traversed and yet is not
discouraged. The fact that scholarship is never finished gives new meaning in a
gospel setting to the commandment to "endure to the end." Eventually, being a
gospel scholar becomes less of a destination and more of a journey. The trip is
difficult at times, but it is doable and full of satisfying rewards.

Ultimately, the challenge is to look into your heart and decide that you really
want to walk the path of becoming a scripture scholar, eventually coming to love
the words, the principles, thoughts, and experiences on each page of scripture.

If you do, the human beings who stand behind those words will become welcome
friends in your life. Each verse or chapter will be cherished, like a dear
friend. Each time you open the scriptures, you will want to hear what your
friend has to say to you. You will remember those messages, each like a separate
picture in a treasured photo album.
\end{quote}

\subsection{What is the purpose of me studying?}

\subsubsection{How}

Russell M. Nelson, ``Four Steps to Learning,'' Tambuli, Sep 1989, 39
\begin{quote}
\begin{itemize}
 \item "Have a great desire to know the truth."
\item "Study with an inquiring mind."
\item "Apply or practice your learning in your daily lives." [See notes on
``Applying
what you learn'']
\item "Pray for help."
\end{itemize}
\end{quote}

\noindent Note, Questions Section
\begin{itemize}
\item I have experiences with people who studied extra hours on their missions,
yet their knowledge wasn't as good as I would expect. What is the formula to
building a strong understanding of the gospel, if not hours of study. (In these
cases, the people were faithful. Is the prideful point of view that some people
simply are smarter than others the correct one in this case?)
	\begin{itemize}
\item  How do I gain more gospel knowledge?
		\begin{itemize}
                \item  From mission journal: Intensify prayer, ask
questions, see pieces of the puzzle which I don't quite understand.
		\item Thought (2009.10.20): We are taught to ``search,
ponder, and pray''. I learned in institute that many of the revelations in the
D\&C came after pondering the scriptures. It was also commented that it is
better to study for a set period of time than to force oneself to finish a block
of reading---one can ponder a single verse for an hour and gain more from one's
study than by reading without pondering.
		\item Thought (2010.10.11): The formula for effective
study in anything is not simply hours of study.  I have experienced firsthand in
college this idea.  I studied much less than others I have observed, yet I
studied ``smarter not harder.''  Is it that some people are simply smarter than
others?  I would say that it is the case that some people study in a more
efficient and effective way than others.  Anyone could adapt smart study skills
if taught correctly.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\vspace{1 em}

