\subsection{Memorization of Scriptures}

Ezra Taft Benson, ``Think on Christ,'' \textit{Ensign}, Apr. 1984, 11
\begin{quote}
``It is our privilege to store our memories with good and great thoughts and
bring them out on the stage of our minds at will. When the Lord faced His three
great temptations in the wilderness, He immediately rebutted the devil with
appropriate scripture which He had stored in His memory''
\end{quote}

\noindent Richard G. Scott, ``Four Fundamentals for Those Who Teach and Inspire
Youth,'' in Old Testament Symposium Speeches, 1987, 5
\begin{quote}
``There is a power that can change lives in the specific words recorded in the
standard works. That power is weakened when we paraphrase or alter the actual
wording. I therefore suggest that you encourage students to cite scripture
content with precision. All you do to encourage students to memorize selected
scriptures accurately will bring to bear in their lives the power of their
content.''
\end{quote}

\noindent Richard G. Scott, in Conference Report, Oct. 1999, 112; or Ensign,
Nov. 1999, 87-88
\begin{quote}
``I suggest that you memorize scriptures that touch your heart and fill your
soul
with understanding. When scriptures are used as the Lord has caused them to be
recorded, they have intrinsic power that is not communicated when paraphrased.
Sometimes when there is a significant need in my life, I review mentally
scriptures that have given me strength. There is great solace, direction, and
power that flow from the scriptures, especially the words of the Lord.''
\end{quote}

\noindent Spencer W. Kimball, in Conference Report, Oct. 1975, 119; or Ensign,
Nov. 1975, 79
\begin{quote}
``I am wondering how many of you know the Articles of Faith? How many of you big
men, as well as the little men? Do you know them? Have you repeated them? You
are always prepared with a sermon when you know the Articles of Faith. And they
are basic, aren't they? I'd think it would be a wonderful thing if all the boys,
as they learn them, would learn them word-perfect. That means that you don't
miss and you don't forget.

``Shall I tell you how I did it? . . . I used to milk cows. I typed with two
fingers, and I would type out these Articles of Faith on little cards and put
them down in the corral right by me when I sat on the one-legged stool and
milked the cows. And I repeated them over, I guess 20 million times. I don't
know. But at any rate, I have claimed that I could say the Articles of Faith now
after these many, many years and could say them word-perfect. And I think it has
been most valuable to me. Will you do that, my fine young men?''
\end{quote}

\subsection{What?}

Henry B. Eyring, ``A Discussion on Scripture Study,'' Ensign, Jul 2005, 22-26
\begin{itemize}
\item Sometimes I go to the scriptures for doctrine. Sometimes I go to the
scriptures for instruction. I go with a question, and the question usually is
``What would God have me do?'' or ``What would He have me feel?'' Invariably I
find
new ideas, thoughts I have never had before, and I receive inspiration and
instruction and answers to my questions.
\item Going to the scriptures to learn what to do makes all the difference. The
Lord
can teach us. When we come to a crisis in our life, such as losing a child or
spouse, we should go looking in the scriptures for specific help. We will find
answers in the scriptures. The Lord seemed to anticipate all of our problems and
all of our needs, and He put help in the scriptures for us---if only we seek it.
\end{itemize}

\noindent Gordon B. Hinckley, ``Feasting upon the Scriptures,'' Ensign, Dec
1985,
42
\begin{quote}
I do not claim distinction as a scholar of the scriptures. For me, the reading
of the scriptures is not the pursuit of scholarship. Rather, it is a love affair
with the word of the Lord and that of his prophets. They contain so much for
each of us.
\end{quote}

	My Take on this Quote: President Hinckley is emphasizing that learning
valuable gospel principles is more important than gaining knowledge of the
doctrine.

\subsubsection{Combating Apathy}

{\it Thought, 2013.04.15:} I have in the past long while had a hard time
getting excited about scripture study. In the past week and a half I have been
inspired to clean up many of my bad habits, and lack of scripture study is one
of those.

Part of my problem is that I didn't feel an urgent need to study the
scriptures.  On the one hand, I have an adequate understanding of the
principles of the gospel.  I am smart enough to understand things which are
said in church.  Therefore, I can adequately associate myself with church
members and not feel that I don't know enough about the gospel.
On the other hand, I have felt apathetic towards standing out in church.  I
haven't had a desire to make insightful comments in Sunday school.

As I have dedicated myself to studying every day, other than having the spirit
with me, I have found that I have actually learned a lot during my scripture
study.  It turns out that even though I have been through a mission, institute,
and years of personal scripture study, it has been as if there are tons of
things sitting on the surface for me to pick up and learn for the first time.
It is humbling.


\subsection{Family Scripture Study}

Henry B. Eyring, ``A Discussion on Scripture Study,'' Ensign, Jul 2005, 22-26
\begin{quote}
For me at least, and I think my six children would agree, scripture study works
well only if your children know you love the scriptures and they also know as
individuals that you love them. Then whatever pattern you have will work. If
scripture study is forced for either them or you, if your children feel pushed,
or if you don't really love the scriptures yourself, then scripture study
doesn't have as much power.
\end{quote}

\subsection{Applying what you learn}

PMG, p. 19: "Live What You Learn"
\begin{quote}
"Acting on what you have learned will bring added and enduring understanding."
\end{quote}

\noindent John 7:17
\begin{quote}
"If any man will do his will, he shall know of the doctrine, whether it be of
God, or whether I speak of myself."
\end{quote}

\noindent PMG, p. 23: "Apply and Live What You Learn"
\begin{quote}
\begin{itemize}
  \item "Liken" what you learn to yourself (1 Nephi 19:23).
\item Set goals to live what you are learning.
\item Subsitute your name in a verse of scripture to personalize it.
\item Ask yourself, "How should I change as a result of what I have learned?"
Set appropriate goals.
\end{itemize}
\end{quote}

