\subsection{Marking the Scriptures}

Handout: Joseph Smith---Matthew with markings

\noindent Handout: Boyd K. Packer, ``Scriptures''

\vspace{1 em}

\noindent Scripture Study Institute Manual
\begin{quote}
 Purposes of Marking Scripture
\begin{itemize}
\item To emphasize
\item To find quickly
\item To make the scriptures personal
\item To teach more easily from the scriptures
\end{itemize}
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Things I Like About Marking the Scriptures}

\begin{itemize}
 \item It aids visual learning
 \item It is a fast way to take notes on scripture study
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Personal Concerns About Marking the Scriptures}

\begin{itemize}
\item When one opens a marked set of scriptures, the markings imply to the mind
what is important in that passage.  This closes off, to a point, the other
insights to be gained from a passage
\begin{itemize}
\item Solution: buy new sets of scriptures to mark; don't always read
from a marked set but read from a clean set or an electronic version.
\item {\it Thought, 2013.04.10:} This is a bit of an excuse.  Studying the
scriptures and being attentive will solve a lot of this problem.
\end{itemize}
\item When working with one set, once a section has a lot of marking to it, I
can't mark anything else without diminishing the value of the markings there
\begin{itemize}
\item Solution: get a new set to mark, and keep all old sets for
reference
\end{itemize}
\item It is not a solution for containing all of my notes on a passage.  There
is not enough room to do that justice.
\begin{itemize}
\item Solution: keep more comprehensive notes in another place (I prefer
document files)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Electronic vs. Print}

Thoughts, 2010.11.15:
I think it is not a simple discussion of saying one should be used universally
over the other.  There are different contexts in which scriptures and notes are
used:
Personal study,
At home,
On the go,
Public use,
Sacrament meeting,
Sunday school,
Priesthood,
Institute,
Firesides.

So I see advantages and disadvantages to each thing

\begin{tabular}{c | c}
 Electronic Devices & Traditional Printed Books\\
\hline
portable & sunday school flipping \\
organizable and changeable & Notes are faster to take \\
Avoid the downsides of marking  & visual marks\\
 quicker list of notes to each passage &
more personal \\
& easier to teach from \\
& colored footnotes \\
\end{tabular}


