\subsection{What the scriptures are not:}

Note, 2011.05.20
\begin{itemize}
\item They are not just for scattering quotes through talks.
\item They are not only for those with leadership callings.
\item They are not only for those called to teach gospel doctrine.
\item They are not only for a quick fix.
\item They are not boring.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Comparing it to studying math}

Thought 11.27.12: In math, I see that one needs to figure things out for
oneself.  In scripture study, does the same hold?  Of the top of my head, I can
say that I don't currently feel the need to go through things quickly, so I
don't really lose anything by going slowly and figuring things out.

\subsection{Questions}
\begin{itemize}
 \item I have experiences with people who studied extra hours on their
missions, yet
their knowledge wasn't as good as I would expect. What is the formula to
building a strong understanding of the gospel, if not hours of study. (In these
cases, the people were faithful. Is the prideful point of view that some people
simply are smarter than others the correct one in this case?)
\begin{itemize}
 \item 	Thought (2010.10.27): I have come upon ideas toward answering this
question
\begin{itemize}
 \item There are ways of studying ``smarter'' not ``harder''.  These
don't have to do with natural intelligence per se and can be learned.  In some
ways these are the same as techniques which help one to succeed at school.
		\item On the other hand, gospel study is distinctly different
from
school in that one has his own agenda.  What one studies and for what purpose is
up to the individual.  Could it be that this contributes to this learning gap?
How does a lack of good study goals hinder one's progress?
\end{itemize}
\item Thought (2012.10.09):
\begin{itemize}
 \item The main people I think of with this issue are righteous people who have
blessings in their lives.  I cannot rule out those people having received their
reward for their extra scripture study.
 \item My current view is that yes, some people are just smarter.
I have been very blessed with not needing to put forth a lot of effort to learn.
\end{itemize}
\item	Sub-question: How do I gain more gospel knowledge?
\begin{itemize}
\item (From mission journal) Intensify prayer, ask questions, see
pieces of the puzzle which I don't quite understand.
	\item 	Thought (2009.10.20): We are taught to ``search, ponder, and
pray''. I learned in institute that many of the revelations in the D\&C came
after pondering the scriptures. It was also commented that it is better to study
for a set period of time than to force oneself to finish a block of
reading---one
can ponder a single verse for an hour and gain more from one's study than by
reading without pondering.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

