\section{Teaching}

Note, Church, 2010.10.18

How does gospel teaching relate to my math teaching.
As a math teacher, I am sure to review the fundamentals.

\vspace{1 em}

\noindent Note, Church, 2010.10.18

I notice that sometimes we have the phrase, ``don't give the primary answers.''
 I
am now thinking that this is a bad attitude.
The primary answers are the most important things.  When given great focus and
attention, they will yield amazing results.
When we have this attitude, we have the attitude of looking to ``good'' things
or
``better'' things instead of the ``best'' things.

\subsection{Teaching With Questions}

Boyd K. Packer, Teach Ye Diligently, p.74
\begin{quote}
It is important for a teacher to make sure that the students understand there is
only one stupid question, and that is the one that is never asked.
\end{quote}
What Is the Purpose of Question Asking?

Boyd K. Packer, Teach Ye Diligently, p.65

\begin{quote}
The simplest way to learn something is to ask a question about it.
\end{quote}

Preach My Gospel, p.183
\begin{quote}
Good questions will help you understand interests, concerns, or questions that
others have.  They can enhance your teaching, invite the spirit, and help your
investigators learn.
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Scriptural Examples}

Teaching, No Greater Call, p. 68
\begin{quote}
Jesus Christ, the Master Teacher, often asked questions to encourage people to
ponder and apply the principles He taught (see, for example, Matthew 16:13-15;
Luke 7:41-42; 3 Nephi 27:27). His questions prompted thought, soul-searching,
and commitment.
\end{quote}

Boyd K. Packer, Teach Ye Diligently, p.65
\begin{quote}
In all training and teaching and classroom situations we find the question. This
was true of Jesus as He taught His disciples or the multitudes. There is
something interesting and meaningful about the way He handled questions and
answers. He asked many questions. He answered but a few of them.
\end{quote}

\textbf{The Spirit of the Lord to Nephi}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Behold, what desirest thou? (1 Nephi 11:2.)
 \item Believest thou that thy father saw the tree of which he hath spoken? (1
Nephi 11:4.)
 \item What desirest thou? (1 Nephi 11:10.)
 \item Knowest thou the condescension of God? (1 Nephi 11:16.)
 \item Knowest thou the meaning of the tree which thy father saw? (1 Nephi
11:21.)
 \item Thou rememberest the twelve apostles of the Lamb? (1 Nephi 12:9.)
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{What to Do and What not to Do}

From Teaching, No Greater Call p. 68

\begin{quote}
\begin{itemize}
 \item Ask questions that learners can answer
 \item Respond to incorrect answers with respect and courtesy
 \item Wait for responses
 \item Use follow-up questions
 \item Give everyone an opportunity to speak
 \item Help learners prepare to answer questions
 \item Avoid questions that create controversy or encourage argument
 \item Occasionally ask questions that prompt silent reflection
\end{itemize}
\end{quote}

Preach My Gospel, p. 183-184
\begin{quote}
 Try to ask questions that:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Are simple and easy to understand.
 \item Help people think about what you are teaching.
 \item Help you determine how well the investigator understands what you are
teaching.
 \item Help people apply what they learn.
\end{itemize}

$\ldots$Avoid asking questions that:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Include more than one idea.
 \item  Pertain to doctrines you have not taught yet.
 \item Do not have a clear purpose.
 \item Interrogate and pry unnecessarily.
\end{itemize}
\end{quote}

Teaching, No Greater Call p. 68
\begin{quote}
When asking [questions that prompt deeper thinking], be open to all answers (see
``Listening,'' pages 66-67). Encourage learners to ponder the scriptures and
gospel principles being discussed and to express their ideas. Do not try to get
them to give specific answers to questions; they will quickly become aware of
what you are doing and either stop participating or start guessing instead of
thinking. When you need a specific answer, it is best to ask a factual question
or present the information in some other way.
\end{quote}

Thought, Study, 2010.11.17
\begin{quote}
I notice that with the ``guess what I am thinking'' method, sometimes teachers
using this method rely on the students giving the correct answer to segue to
their next point.
\end{quote}

Thoughts on Boyd K. Packer, Teach Ye Diligently, p.72-74
\begin{quote}
He talks about asking good questions and how it will help the class participate.
 He gives three examples of questions:

``Would you give me the year, the month, the day, and the time of day that the
Prophet Joseph Smith was martyred in Carthage Jail?''

``A much better question would be, "In reviewing Church history, let me remind
you that it was in the afternoon of June 27, 1844, that the Prophet Joseph Smith
was killed. We know about what time it was because the watch that John Taylor
wore was struck by a bullet and stopped at that hour. Tell me, please, why was
Joseph Smith willing to go to Carthage when he knew what would probably take
place?"

"In your opinion, why did Joseph Smith go to Carthage when he knew he would be
in danger?"

These questions are in ascending order of effectiveness.
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{What Happens When Poor Questions Are Asked}

Preach My Gospel, p.183
\begin{quote}
Poor questions can intimidate, irritate, and offend investigators.  They can
also cause you to lose control of the teaching situation.
\end{quote}

Thoughts on Boyd K. Packer, Teach Ye Diligently, p.72-74
\begin{quote}
He says that poor question asking causes the students to participate less, if at
all.
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Types of Questions}

\textit{From Teaching, No Greater Call p. 68}

\vspace{1 em}

\noindent \textit{Questions that can be answered yes or no}
\begin{quote}
``Questions that can be answered yes or no have limited use in gospel
instruction. You should use them primarily to obtain commitments or to determine
if someone agrees or disagrees.''
\end{quote}

\noindent \textit{Factual questions}
\begin{quote}
``Make sure that you do not ask only factual questions. They do not require much
thought, and they may discourage those who do not know the answers. When you do
use them, you should generally make sure that the information necessary to
answer them is available to those you teach.''

	``With factual questions, you can help everyone begin a discussion at
the
same point. You can then move to questions that prompt deeper thinking and help
learners see how gospel principles apply in their lives.''
\end{quote}

\noindent \textit{Questions that prompt deeper thinking}
\begin{quote}
``These questions often begin with the words what, how, or why. They cannot be
answered with yes or no, and they usually have more than one right answer.''
Questions that help learners apply gospel principles

``Ask learners to share examples of how they or others have applied the gospel
principles being discussed. As prompted by the Spirit, encourage them to bear
testimony of the principles they discuss.''
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Answering a Question with a Question}

Boyd K. Packer, Teach Ye Diligently, p.66
\begin{quote}
Contrary to what you may suppose, the Lord generally did not answer
questions--at least not in the usual way, particularly the questions that came
from those who were tempting Him. Generally He did not answer them with a direct
answer or an explanation. In fact, He almost always responded by asking a
question of those who raised the question in the first place.
Creative Uses of Questions
\end{quote}

Teaching, No Greater Call p. 68
\begin{quote}
You may want to use questions in some of the following ways:

Write questions on wordstrips, and tape the wordstrips to the bottoms of chairs.
At appropriate times during the discussion, ask each person to remove the
question from his or her chair. Then have him or her read the question and
respond to it.

Ask each learner to write one question based on a gospel principle or verse of
scripture. Gather the questions and discuss them.

Ask individuals to role-play characters of their choice in the lesson, and let
the others ask them questions (see ``Role Playing,'' page 178). This works
particularly well with children.

During the week before the lesson, give questions to a few learners. Ask them to
prepare to respond to those questions as part of the coming lesson.

Use the following questions to discuss a gospel principle: ``What do we already
know about this principle?'' ``What do we want to know?'' ``What have we learned
today?'' You can form the basis of the lesson by having learners answer these
questions and then writing their answers in three columns on the chalkboard.
Write a question on the chalkboard before class begins so that learners can
begin pondering it as soon as they arrive.

Have learners answer questions by finding and reading appropriate scriptures or
hymns. Ask learners to respond to questions by sharing examples from their own
lives.

Divide the class into small groups. Give each group a few questions to consider.
Then have each group report their answers to the class.
\end{quote}

