\section{Thoughts}

Keeping one's thoughts clean brings power.
Keeping one's thoughts positive brings power.

Proverbs 23:7: ``For as he thinketh in his heart, so is he$\ldots$''

\subsection{Central Topic}

Personal Insight, 2012.04.23
\begin{quote}
``Thoughts" is a central topic (like pride).  Mastery of this one thing
necessarily implies obedience to the gospel and therefore success in everything.
 Failure in this one thing implies disobedience, lack of spirituality, and
therefore failure in life.
\end{quote}

\subsection{Appropriate Media}

Pres. Thomas S. Monson, ``Great Expectations'', CES Fireside 2009.01.04
\begin{quote}
``Don't be afraid to walk out of a movie, turn off a television set, or
change the radio station if what's being presented does not meet your Heavenly
Father's standards. In short, if you have any question about whether a
particular movie, book, or other form of entertainment is appropriate, don't see
it, don't read it, don't participate.''
\end{quote}

Notes, Church, 2009.02.08
\begin{quote}
The Lord wouldn't command us to have virtuous thoughts if it were impossible.
Our mind is a stage--there is always something on it.
Thoughts are like water--they follow the path of least resistance.
Choose a favorite hymn for the hour of temptation.
``Evil cannot tolerate the presence of light''.
Charity + Virtue $\Rightarrow$ confidence in the presence of God.
\end{quote}

\subsection{The Lord Never Had Unclean Thoughts}

Stephen Robinson, Believing Christ, 115
\begin{quote}
Do not misunderstand me.  I am not suggesting here that Jesus in any way
indulged in unclean thoughts, for that would be sin, and he indulged in nothing
sinful.  I do not believe that he ‘struggled' or ‘wrestled' with temptations.
My only point is that he was as vulnerable to suggestions and impulses coming
into his mind from his mortal nature, a nature inherited from his mortal mother,
as any of us.  He simply paid no attention to those suggestions, and he
immediately put them out of his mind.  The ability of the flesh to suggest, to
entice, was the same for him as it is for us, but unlike the rest of us, he
never responded to it.  He didn't ponder, deliberate, or entertain the sinful
options even as theoretical possibilities--''he gave no heed unto them.''
\end{quote}

\section{Tragedy of the Commons}

This is about individual behaviors which
\begin{enumerate}
 \item when taken by an individual individual within a group benefit that
individual, but
 \item when taken by a large number of the individuals in the group harm
everyone.
\end{enumerate}

Examples:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Poluting
 \item Not voting
 \item Population growth
 \item Stealing
 \item Spam email
 \item Using the freeways
\end{itemize}

The gospel teaches us that there are behaviors which we should adopt which fight
this phenomenon:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Giving to the poor
 \item Service
 \item Honesty
 \item Chastity
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Careful!}

Ultimately, the gospel transcends this topic.
We would still follow the gospel even if it didn't do these things for us.

\section{Translated Beings}

\subsection{Transfiguration, Translation, and Resurrection}

\subsubsection{Transfiguration}

Mormon Doctrine, ``Transfiguration''
\begin{quote}
Transfiguration is a special change in appearance and nature which is wrought
upon by a person or thing by the power of God.  This divine transformation is
from a lower to a higher state; it results in a more exalted, impressive, and
glorious condition.
Prophets we translated to be able to stand in the presence of God.
Transfiguration is temporary: those who are translated return to the lower state
of mere mortality.
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Translation}
Teachings, p.170-171
\begin{quote}
``[A] distinction is made between the doctrine of the actual resurrection and
translation: translation obtains deliverance from the tortures and sufferings of
the body, but their existence will prolong as to the labors and toils of the
ministry, before they can enter into so great a rest and glory.''
See 3 Ne. 28 for a description of the three Nephites state as translated beings.
These beings die and are resurrected in a twinkling of an eye. (See Mormon
Doctrine, ``Translated Beings'')
\end{quote}

\subsubsection{Resurrection}
A permanent state which occurs after death. We receive a perfect body.


\subsection{Examples of Translated Beings}

\begin{itemize}
 \item Mormon Doctrine, ``Translated Beings''
\begin{quote}
	Enoch and his people were translated, probably just a few years after
Adam's death. (Moses 7:18-21, 31, 63, 69; D. \& C. 38:4; 45:11-14; 84:99-100;
Gen. 5:22-24; Heb. 11:5.)
\end{quote}
 \item TJS Gen. 14:32-34: Melchizedek and his people
 \item Alma 45:18-19: Moses
 \subitem Mormon Doctrine, ``Translated Beings''
\begin{quote}
	The Old Testament account that Moses died and was buried by the hand of
the Lord in an unknown grave is an error. (Deut. 34:5-7.) It is true that he may
have been "buried by the hand of the Lord," if that expression is a figure of
speech which means that he was translated.
\end{quote}
 \item 2 Kings 2: Elijah
 \subitem Mormon Doctrine, ``Translated Beings''
\begin{quote}
	Moses and Elijah were translated so that they could come with bodies of
flesh and bones to confer keys upon Peter, James, and John on the mount of
transfiguration, an event destined to occur prior to the beginning of the
resurrection. (Matt. 17:1-6; Teachings, p. 158; Doctrines of Salvation, vol. 2,
pp. 107-111.)
\end{quote}
 \item Alma the Younger
 \subitem Teachings, p. 170.
\begin{quote}
	Translated beings are "held in reserve to be ministering angels unto
many planets."
\end{quote}
 \item John the Revelator (John 21:20-23; Rev. 10; D. \& C. 7; 77:14.)
\item The three Nephites (3 Ne. 28)
\end{itemize}

\section{Zion}

\begin{itemize}
 \item D\&C 97:21: ``This is Zion--The Pure in Heart.''
 \item 3 Ne. 12:8: ``Blessed are all the pure in heart, for they shall see
God.''
\end{itemize}

\noindent Elder D. Todd Christofferson, ``Come to Zion'', Oct. 2008 Conference
\begin{quote}
 Zion is both a place and a people. Zion was the name given to the
ancient city of Enoch in the days before the Flood. "And it came to pass in his
days, that he built a city that was called the City of Holiness, even Zion"
(Moses 7:19). This Zion endured for some 365 years (see Moses 7:68). The
scriptural record states, "And Enoch and all his people walked with God, and he
dwelt in the midst of Zion; and it came to pass that Zion was not, for God
received it up into his own bosom; and from thence went forth the saying, Zion
is fled" (Moses 7:69). Later, Jerusalem and its temple were called Mount Zion,
and the scriptures prophesy of a future New Jerusalem where Christ shall reign
as "King of Zion," when "for the space of a thousand years the earth shall rest"
(Moses 7:53, 64).

	The Lord called Enoch's people Zion "because they were of one heart and
one mind, and dwelt in righteousness; and there was no poor among them" (Moses
7:18). Elsewhere He said, "For this is Zion---the pure in heart" (D\&C 97:21).
\end{quote}


\noindent Mormon Doctrine
\begin{quote}
Zion is the name given by the Lord to his saints$\ldots$

The city of Enoch was called ``the City of Holiness, even Zion.''

The name Zion was applied to one of the hills upon which Jerusalem is built or
(later) to the entire city.

The New Jerusalem to be built in Jackson County, Missouri, is also called the
City of Zion or Zion.

Joseph Smith announced at the April, 1844, general conference of the Church that
all of North and South America comprise the Land of Zion.

At the Second Coming, ``the Lamb shall stand upon Mount Zion$\ldots$'' The Mount
Zion
spoken of is$\ldots$the New Jerusalem to be built in Jackson County, Missouri
(D\&C
84:1-4).

Paul uses the term Mount Zion to refer to the abode of exalted beings (Heb
12:22-24).
\end{quote}

JST, Gen. 14:33-35: Melchizedek was translated with his people.
Jerusalem will be the religious capital, New Jerusalem will be the legislative
capital
People will still live everywhere. Zion is people. Where there is a stake, there
Zion is by extension.

\subsection{Building Zion}

D\&C 105:5: ``And Zion cannot be built up unless it is by the principles of the
law of the celestial kingdom; otherwise I cannot receive her unto myself.''

Zion will be built during the Millenium.

